description: Introduced invasive pigs, although (success!) these animals no longer occur on the island. Kiwis were there while I was there, trying to eradicate them. They were successful just six months later. The last feral pig was destroyed on July 5, 2006, and the native flora is reportedly on the rebound. Here's a fun sounding article: Rapid eradication of feral pigs (Sus scrofa) from Santa Cruz Island, California "In 411 days, a total of 5036 pigs were removed....Sterilized adult pigs fitted with radio collars were subsequently used to aid in the location of surviving wild pigs and to monitor the success of the project. Female telemetered pigs were more effective than males at locating remaining wild pigs. Only 10% of the last 102 pigs (the last 20 or so present in each fenced zone) were dispatched as a result of being found with a telemetered pig, but telemetered animals were responsible for finding 43% of the very last pigs once normal hunting had ceased." Fishing with female pig.

The island scrub jay (Aphelocoma insularis) alsoknown as the Island Jay or Santa Cruz Jay is endemic to Santa Cruz Island in the Santa Barbara Channel off the coast of Ventura, CA. Of the over 500 breeding bird species in the continental U.S. and Canada, it is the only insular endemic landbird species.  It is approximately 1/3 larger than the Western Scrub Jay found on the mainland and has a brighter color and larger bill.

The large pelicans had very long wingspans, and gracefully soared over the smooth waves. Due to the coloration, these were most likely breeding adult pelicans. The bills were long and pouched, perfect for their appetites. These were the only avian species found out in the open Ocean for the majority of our trip to Santa Cruz Is.

This large humpback whale was an absolute stunner, it breached multiple times (I missed all three opportunities for a photo shot sadly), slapped the surface with the long flippers, and fluked on several dives. A smaller juvenile whale was accompanying this adult in the Ocean waters of the Santa Barbara Channel.

This juvenile humpback whale was an absolute stunner! It slapped the surface with the long flippers, and fluked on several dives. This individual was accompanied by an adult in the Ocean waters of the Santa Barbara Channel.

The large pelicans had very long wingspans, and gracefully soared over the smooth waves. Due to the coloration, these were most likely breeding adult pelicans. A few decided to take a rest from flight on the still waters. These were the only avian species found out in the open Ocean for the majority of our trip to Santa Cruz Is.

The energetic, mobile, close-knit dolphins in this superpod were an exhilarating sight! The groups were made up of calves and adults, which had the gray and light brown coloration. Hundreds and hundreds of these dolphins swam in large pods in the Ocean, we even heard their vocalizations from the surface!

The energetic, mobile, close-knit dolphins were an exhilarating sight! The groups were made up of calves and adults, which had the gray and light brown coloration. As the boat began to speed up, the dolphins began to bow-ride with us, and before we knew it they all were bounding speedily along our sides. These dolphins were part of a superpod which lived in the open Ocean.

The large sea lion swam stealthily through the calm waters, seen due to its need to breathe. No other birds or marine mammals surrounded it, only the sea lion and the mighty Ocean were seen during this chunk of the boat ride.

The large, black bird had a thick, "square" tail, thick beak, and a croak-like call that was deep, unlike the crow. It perched on the rocks nearby the shore and continued to walk along the path. Its thick beak, glossy feathers, and bead-like eyes were seen up close in an intriguing way! These ravens were somewhat common on the Rocky Shore.

The small passerine bird was fly-catching at times, repeatedly "hovering" and flying inbetween branches. The plumage was olive-brown and light yellowish-gray. Two of these were present in the shrubs of the Coastal Sage Scrub at the base of the canyon.

These foxes were extremely abundant throughout the campsite, the equivalent to squirrels in an ordinary campground on the mainland! Their pelts were seemingly soft, with gray, orange, and white coloration. They trotted swiftly through the clearings of the Cultivated eucalyptus forest.

description: These foxes were extremely abundant throughout the campsite, the equivalent to squirrels in an ordinary campground on the mainland! Their pelts were seemingly soft, with gray, orange, and white coloration. This one ran swiftly through the underbrush and retreated under a large snag, this could be a mother tending to her young in a den in the deeply shaded Cultivated eucalyptus grove.

The small wren was seen because it was very mobile and energetic, its coloration blended in with the surroundings very well. The feathers were light brown/gray, there was a light band above the eyes, and the body was round and plump. It was seen in the Cultivated eucalyptus forest.

The sparrow was boldly marked, with a reddish-gray back, light belly, and a gray/black streaked head. Its charismatic chirps were heard from the thickets and that's how I eventually found it. These were relatively common at the base of the canyon, in the Coastal Sage Scrub environment with a drainage.
The bird was a small passerine, with a black body and white belly. It flew inbetween the low branches and lawn probably while feeding. It lived in the Cultivated ranch home garden.

The small fox was seen in the open brushing itself with the hind paw, it was adorable beyond compare! The fox's pelt was seemingly soft, with gray, orange, and white coloration. It sat in the open road leading into the Cultivated ranch home garden.

This lizard was young, light in color, and fast with energy. The back was mostly bluish-brown, towards the head and sides the coloration turned more like a yellow-orange with brown blotches. These were seen darting from basking in the sun in large numbers in the Seasonal Grassland.

The accipter was swift in flight, cirlcing around repeatedly over a certain slope like a vulture. Its build was small, even smaller than a Cooper's. It soared over the open Seasonal Grassland for about five minutes.

description: This lizard was young, light in color, and fast with energy. The back was mostly bluish-brown, towards the head and sides the coloration turned more like a yellow-orange with brown blotches. Dozens of these lizards skittered across the trails crisscrossing the Seasonal Grassland.

Rustling under the low-growing shrubs was the ruling land predator the island: the adorable island fox! The fox's pelt was seemingly soft, with gray, orange, and white coloration. It was a shy individual, a sharp contrast in behavior compared to the campsite-dwelling foxes. This little guy went along the limestone Coastal Bluffs as it traveled along.

The two whales were very acrobatic during their swimming, waving their long white and gray flippers and breaching out of the water. The long flippers and the humped back is unique to this species. One calf and an adult were seen swimming in the Ocean waters of the channel.
The gull's beak was mostly yellow, with a little red. The body was white, with dark gray wings. It flew swiftly across the Coastal Bluffs towards the larger kelp flats and the harbor.
Remains of young individual washed ashore.

description: The passerine bird was small, with a dark, slick beak. The wings were brown , along with the head which also had a white "brow" over the eye. The lower belly was rusty orange and the chest was light tan/white. It scaled up the steep Coastal Bluffs a hundred feet up without any error!

The large pelicans had very long wingspans, and gracefully soared over the smooth waves. Due to the coloration, these were most likely breeding adult pelicans. The bills were long and pouched, perfect for their appetites. This one was perched on the rocks nearby the Coastal Bluffs, before it took flight for the larger ocean.

The large, black bird had a thick, "square" tail, thick beak, and a croak-like call that was deep, unlike the crow. It trotted along the bare ground, aggressively approaching some backpackers which were having their lunch! These ravens were abundant around the vicinity of the Coastal Bluffs.
